revision.text:
'''Bettye Anne Busbee Case''' is Olga Larson Professor Emerita of Mathematics at [[Florida State University]].{{r|cv}} Her mathematical research concerns [[Complex analysis|complex variables]]; she has also published on [[mathematics education]] and the [[history of mathematics]].{{r|change}}
She is the editor of the books ''A Century of Mathematical Meetings'' (American Mathematical Society, 1996) and ''Complexities: Women in Mathematics'' (with Anne M. Leggett, Princeton University Press, 2005).{{r|complexities}}

==Education and career==
Case graduated from the [[University of Alabama]] in 1962.{{r|cv}} She earned her Ph.D. in 1970 from the same university; her dissertation, ''On Non-Analytic Functions Related to a System of Partial Differential Equations'', was supervised by Mario O. González.{{r|mgp}} She taught at the [[Florida Institute of Technology]] and then at [[Tallahassee Community College]] for nine years before joining the Florida State University faculty as an associate professor in 1982.{{r|cv}}

Case was the founding director of both the undergraduate program in [[actuarial science]] and the graduate area [[mathematical finance|financial mathematics]] at Florida State.  She was active member of the [[Association for Women in Mathematics]], and coordinated their meetings at mathematics conferences from 1984 to 2015.{{r|change}}

==Recognition==
Florida State named Case the Olga Larson Professor in 2004.{{r|cv}} In 2016 the [[Association for Women in Mathematics]] presented Case a Lifetime Service Award in recognition for her many decades of service to the AWM, particularly as Meetings Coordinator and long time member of the Executive Committee.{{r|lsawm}} {{r|lsawm2}}
In 2018 she was honored as one of the inaugural Fellows of the [[Association for Women in Mathematics]].{{r|fawm}}

