{{Infobox scientist |name = Efim Zelmanov |image =EfimIZelmanov.jpg |image_size =150px |caption = Efim Zelmanov |birth_name=Efim Isaakovich Zelmanov |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|09|07}} |birth_place = [[Khabarovsk]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]] |death_date = |death_place = |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = [[Russia]]n, [[United States|American]] |ethnicity = |field = [[mathematics]] |work_institutions = [[University of California, San Diego]] |alma_mater = |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = {{plainlist| *[[Martin Kassabov]] }} |known_for = [[nonassociative algebra]] |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |prizes = [[Fields Medal]] (1994) |religion = |footnotes = |signature = }}
'''Efim Isaakovich Zelmanov''' ({{lang-ru|Ефи́м Исаа́кович Зе́льманов}}; born 7 September 1955 in [[Khabarovsk]]) is a [[Russian-American]]<ref>http://www.nasonline.org/member-directory/members/3008679.html</ref> [[mathematician]], known for his work on combinatorial problems in [[nonassociative algebra]] and [[group theory]], including his solution of the [[restricted Burnside problem]]. He was awarded a [[Fields Medal]] at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] in [[Zürich]] in 1994.
Zelmanov was born into a [[Jew]]ish family in [[Khabarovsk]], [[Soviet Union]] (now in [[Russia]]). He entered [[Novosibirsk State University]] in 1972, when he was 17 years old.<ref>[http://faces.nsu.ru/?p=607 Interview with Zelmanov (in Russian)]</ref> He obtained doctoral degree at [[Novosibirsk State University]] in 1980, and a higher degree at [[Leningrad State University]] in 1985. He had a position in Novosibirsk until 1987, when he left the Soviet Union.[[File:Zelmanov and Hunter in Lincoln.jpg|left|thumb|Efim Zelmanov (right) with the [[University of Lincoln]] (UK) Deputy Vice-Chancellor Professor Andrew Hunter (left) after receiving Honorary DSc degree. 5th September 2016, Lincoln, UK.]]In 1990 he moved to the [[United States]], becoming a professor at the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]]. He was at the [[University of Chicago]] in 1994/5, then at [[Yale University]]. As of 2011, he is a professor at the [[University of California, San Diego]]<ref>{{cite web|title=UCSD Press Releases: Fields Medalist Joins Mathematics Faculty at UCSD|url=http://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/newsrel/science/mczelmanov.htm}}</ref> and a Distinguished Professor at the [[Korea Institute for Advanced Study]]. Zelmanov was elected a member of the [[U.S. National Academy of Sciences]] in 2001,<ref>[http://www.ams.org/notices/200107/people.pdf National Academy of Sciences Elections], [[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]] '''48''' (2001), no. 7, p. 722</ref> becoming, at the age of 47, the youngest member of the mathematics section of the academy.<ref>[http://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/archive/newsrel/science/mczelmanov.htm FIELDS MEDALIST JOINS MATHEMATICS FACULTY AT UCSD], [[University of California at San Diego]] news release, October 28, 2002</ref> He is also an elected member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] (1996)<ref>[http://www.ams.org/notices/199607/people.pdf American Academy Elections], [[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]] '''43''' (1996), no. 7, p. 781</ref> and a foreign member of the [[Korean Academy of Science and Engineering]] and of the [[Spanish Royal Academy of Sciences]].<ref>[http://news.ualberta.ca/newsreleases/2011/06/efimzelmanovtoreceivehonorarydoctorofsciencedegreefromuniversityofalberta Efim Zelmanov to receive honorary doctor of science degree from University of Alberta] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422165320/http://news.ualberta.ca/newsreleases/2011/06/efimzelmanovtoreceivehonorarydoctorofsciencedegreefromuniversityofalberta |date=2014-04-22 }}, [[University of Alberta]] press release, June 14, 2011</ref> In 2012 he became a fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society], retrieved 2013-09-01.</ref>
Zelmanov gave invited talks at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] in Warsaw (1983), Kyoto (1990) and Zurich (1994).<ref>[http://www.ams.org/notices/199808/bios-all.pdf Biographies of candidates 1998], [[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]] '''45''' (1998), no. 8, p. 1018</ref> He was awarded Honorary Doctor degrees from the University of Alberta, Canada (2011),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ualberta.ca/news-and-events/newsarticles/2011/04/honourarydegreerecipientssettoinspire|title=Honorary degree recipients set to inspire - University of Alberta|website=www.ualberta.ca|access-date=2016-09-08|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913214403/https://www.ualberta.ca/news-and-events/newsarticles/2011/04/honourarydegreerecipientssettoinspire|archivedate=2016-09-13|df=}}</ref> Shevchenko National University of Kyiv, Ukraine (2012),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.univ.kiev.ua/en/geninf/hdoc/|title=Honorary Doctors|website=www.univ.kiev.ua|access-date=2016-09-08}}</ref> the Universidad Internacional Menéndez Pelayo in Santander, Spain (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lne.es/sociedad-cultura/2015/02/07/otin-zelmanov-doctores-honoris-causa/1709850.html|title=Otín y Zelmanov, doctores honoris causa por la Universidad Menéndez Pelayo|last=España|first=La Nueva|access-date=2016-09-08}}</ref> and the [[University of Lincoln]], UK (2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsletter.lms.ac.uk/visit-of-professor-efim-zelmanov/|title=Visit of Professor Efim Zelmanov {{!}} LONDON MATHEMATICAL SOCIETY NEWSLETTER|last=|first=|date=July 11, 2016|website=newsletter.lms.ac.uk|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.uk/news/2016/08/1258.asp|title=Celebrating degree success as Class of 2016 graduate|last=University of Lincoln|first=|date=31 August 2016|website=University of Lincoln Press Office|publisher=|language=en|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref>
Zelmanov's early work was on [[Jordan algebra]]s in the case of infinite dimensions. He was able to show that [[Glennie's identity]] in a certain sense generates all identities that hold. He then showed that the [[Engel identity]] for [[Lie algebra]]s implies [[nilpotent Lie algebra|nilpotence]], in the case of infinite dimensions.
